: #20, {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Stefano Eranio]], 24 ([[Rory Delap]] has 24 starts as a right midfielder)\n* CF: #8, {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Dean Sturridge]], 30\n* LF: #9, {{flagicon|CRC}} [[Paulo Wanchope]], 37\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Derby County F.C. seasons}}\n{{1998\u201399 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1998-99 Derby County F.C. season}}\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:1998\u201399 FA Premier League by team|Derby County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club              = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n| season            = [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]]\n| manager           = [[Jim Smith (footballer)|Jim Smith]]\n| chairman          = [[Lionel Pickering]]\n| stadium           = [[Pride Park Stadium|Pride Park]]\n| league            = [[Premier League|FA Premier League]]\n| league result     = [[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|8th]]\n| cup1              = [[FA Cup]]\n| cup1 result       = [[1998\u201399 FA Cup#Sixth round proper|Quarter-finals]]\n| cup2              = [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| cup2 result       = [[1998\u201399 Football League Cup#Third round|Third round]]\n| league topscorer  = [[Paulo Wanchope|Wanchope]]/[[Deon Burton|Burton]] (9)\n| season topscorer  = Burton (12)\n| highest attendance= 32,913 (vs. [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], 13 March)\n| lowest attendance = 21,037 (vs. [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]], 22 August)\n| average attendance= 29,193\n| prevseason        = [[1997\u201398 Derby County F.C. season|1997\u201398]]\n| nextseason        = [[1999\u20132000 Derby County F.C. season|1999\u20132000]]\n}}\nThe [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399 English football season]] was [[Derby County F.C.]]'s third consecutive season in the [[Premier League]].\n\n==Season summary==\nDerby's second tilt at European football was made in the 1998\u201399 season, the Rams peaking in 2nd place after 6 games with a 2\u20130 home win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], eventually finishing one place better off in 8th. They reached the FA Cup Quarter finals for the third time in seven years, losing out only to late [[Nwankwo Kanu]] goal in a 0\u20131 away defeat to Arsenal, and recorded some memorable victories, including a league double over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] 2\u20131 at [[Anfield]] and 3\u20132 at [[Pride Park Stadium|Pride Park]] and a 1\u20130 win over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the teams first ever meeting at Pride Park. Derby County were a club on the up; Pride Park's capacity was expanded (32,913 fans attended the 3\u20132 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]) and Derby's players were getting noticed \u2013 five had represented their countries at the [[1998 World Cup]], and [[Christian Dailly]] was sold to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] for \u00a35.35m, comfortably the highest fee Derby had ever received. The key departure, however, was [[Steve McClaren]] \u2013 Smith's number two since he had taken the Derby managerial position 3 years earlier \u2013 who departed in February 1999 to become [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]]'s assistant at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], winning [[the treble]] in his first [[1998\u201399 Manchester United F.C. season|3 months at Old Trafford]]. The 1998\u201399 season was Jim Smith's Derby County peak, as the financial demands of Premier League football began to catch up with them.\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|1998\u201399 FA Premier League}}\n{{:1998\u201399 FA Premier League|showteam=DER}}\n\n;Results summary\n{{Fb_rs|hw=8|hd=7|hl=4|hgf=22|hga=19|aw=5|ad=6|al=8|agf=18|aga=26}}\n{{Fb_rs_footer|s=[http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=115 1998-99 FA Premier League table]|date=August 2015}}\n\n;Results by round\n{{#invoke:sports rbr table|t