rs/season/1999</ref>\n* GK: #1, {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Russell Hoult]], 26\n* RB: #3, {{flagicon|GER}} [[Stefan Schnoor]], 25\n* CB: #17, {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Spencer Prior]], 39\n* CB: #2, {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Horacio Carbonari]], 32\n* LB: #16, {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Jacob Laursen]], 44\n* CM: #18, {{flagicon|IRL}} [[Lee Carsley]], 27\n* CM: #4, {{flagicon|JAM}} [[Darryl Powell]], 34\n* CM: #14, {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Lars Bohinen]], 32\n* RF: #20, {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Stefano Eranio]], 24 ([[Rory Delap]] has 24 starts as a right midfielder)\n* CF: #8, {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Dean Sturridge]], 30\n* LF: #9, {{flagicon|CRC}} [[Paulo Wanchope]], 37\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Derby County F.C. seasons}}\n{{1998\u201399 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1998-99 Derby County F.C. season}}\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:1998\u201399 FA Premier League by team|Derby County]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: teams first ever \u2192 teams' first ever", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998%E2%80%9399_Derby_County_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "Jamil Smith (journalist)", "text_new": "{{About|the journalist|the actor|Jamil Walker Smith}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals   = \n| name               =  <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| post-nominals   = \n| image              =  JamilSmith.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| alt                = Headshot of Jamil Smith. He wears glasses, a green-and-black checked collared shirt and a blue Los Angeles Dodgers cap. He smiles, looking off-camera.\n| caption            = Smith in February 2018\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  {{birth date and age|1975|09|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| nationality        = American\n| citizenship        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Journalist|Television producer}}\n| years_active       = 2002&ndash;present\n| employer           = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| known_for          = \n|credits= {{hlist|''[[Inside The NFL]]''|''[[Hard Knocks (TV series)|Hard Knocks]]''|''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]''|[[Melissa Harris-Perry (TV series)|''Melissa Harris-Perry'']] }}\n| home_town          = \n| movement           = \n| boards             = \n| awards             = [[Sports Emmy Award]]s (2006, 2009 and 2010)\n| website            = {{URL|twitter.com/JamilSmith}}\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Jamil Smith''' (born September 23, 1975) is an American print and television journalist. His reporting and commentary deal with a range of political and cultural topics, including race, gender, national politics and pop culture. He has been a senior editor at ''[[The New Republic]]'', a senior national correspondent at [[MTV News]], and is now a senior writer for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.\n\nWhile a television segment producer for [[NFL Films]], Smith won three [[Sports Emmy Award]]s, in 2006, 2009 and 2010. He has also served as a producer for ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' and [[Melissa Harris-Perry (TV series)|''Melissa Harris-Perry'']].\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn September 23, 1975,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JamilSmith/status/911720756949782528|title=My first @nytopinion op-ed, published on my birthday.|last=Smith|first=Jamil|date=September 23, 2017|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.shaker.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=6GUIAI0&dasi=2YB|title=March 2018 Newsletter: Journalist Jamil Smith (\u201893) Returns to SHHS to Discuss His Career and his Time Magazine Cover Story on Black Panther|date=March 2018|website=Shaker Heights Schools|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> in [[Cleveland, Ohio]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/cleveland-native-and-senior-editor-at-the-new-republic-jamil-smith-talks-about-race-his-new-job-the-new-new-republic-and-how-the-media-shou/Content?oid=4568641|title=Cleveland Native and Senior Editor at The New Republic Jamil Smith Talks About His New Job, the New New Republic, and How the Media Should be Covering Race|last=Grzegorek|first=Vince|date=April 29, 2015|website=Cleveland Scene|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Smith attended [[Hawken School]] through eighth grade, then graduated from [[Shaker Heights High School]] in 1993.<ref name=\":1\" /> While at Shaker Heights High School, he wrote for the student newspaper, ''The Shakerite'', for four years,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://shakerite.com/campus-and-city/jamil-smith/23/2018/|title=From The Shakerite to Time Magazine|last=Sheperd|first=Lauren|date=February 23, 2018|work=The Shakerite|access-date=March 17, 2018|last2=Krouse|first2=Anna|language=en-US}}</ref> as well as participating in the wrestling and track teams<ref name=\":1\" /> and the school's Minority Achievement Community program, where black upperclassmen with high grade point averages mentor black freshman and sophomore boys with lower GPAs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSmith did his undergraduate work at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], graduating from the College of Arts and Sciences in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upenn.edu/gazette/0703/0703notes.html|title=Gazette: Alumni Notes|date=July\u2013August 2003|website=www.upenn.edu|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> While in college, Smith wrote for the campus student newspaper, ''[[The Daily Pennsylvanian]]'', and participated in Students Together Against Acquaintance Rape.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.acluohio.org/archives/blog-posts/ten-things-you-need-to-know-about-jamil-smith|title=Ten Things You Need to Know about Jamil Smith|last=Claytor|first=Ifeolu|date=October 5, 2017|website=www.acluohio.org|publisher=ACLU of Ohio|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He also studied abroad at [[King's College London|Kings College London]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\nAfter four years as an assistant at the [[William Morris Agency]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://storify.com/JamilSmith/on-writing-professionally|title=On writing professionally|last=Smith|first=Jamil|date=January 31, 2015|website=Storify|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref> Smith began his career in television and film production in 2002 as a production assistant with [[CNN]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He next went to [[HBO Sports]], then [[NFL Films]],<ref name=\":0\" /> where he worked on production teams that won three [[Sports Emmy Award|Sports Emmys]], two for ''[[Inside the NFL]]'' and another for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] installment of the [[Hard Knocks (TV series)|''Hard Knocks'']] series.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/sports_30th_winners|title=WINNERS OF 30th ANNUAL SPORTS EMMY\u00ae AWARDS ANNOUNCED BY NATIONAL ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS & SCIENCES, DICK EBERSOL HONORED WITH LIFETIME ACHIEVEMENT AWARD |date=April 27, 2009|website=emmyonline.com|publisher=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/sports_31st_winners|title=WINNERS OF 31st ANNUAL SPORTS EMMY\u00ae AWARDS ANNOUNCED BY NATIONAL ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS & SCIENCES, JOHN MADDEN HONORED WITH LIFETIME ACHIEVEMENT AWARD |date=April 26, 2010|website=emmyonline.com|publisher=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, he joined [[MSNBC]], serving as a producer for both ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' and [[Melissa Harris-Perry (TV series)|''Melissa Harris-Perry'']].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/29/business/media/melissa-harris-perry-is-out-at-msnbc-cable-network-confirms.html|title=After Tense Weeks, Melissa Harris-Perry\u2019s MSNBC Show Is Canceled|last1=Koblin|first1=John|date=February 28, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.poynter.org/2015/the-new-republic-begins-replenishing-its-staff/311037/|title=The New Republic begins replenishing its staff|last1=Mullin|first1=Benjamin|date=January 7, 2015|work=Poynter|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs a journalist and commentator, Smith has drawn notice for work on a range of political and cultural topics, including race and racism,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/vice-dubuc-ceo.php|title=The media today: Facing a critical moment, Vice plans for change at the top|last1=Vernon|first1=Pete|date=March 13, 2018|work=Columbia Journalism Review|accessdate=March 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theroot.com/facewall/the-root-100-2015/#jamil_smith|title=The Root 100 \u2013 78 Jamil Smith|last=|first=|date=September 9, 2015|work=The Root|access-date=July 30, 2016|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919164038/http://www.theroot.com/facewall/the-root-100-2015/#jamil_smith|archive-date=September 19, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> police brutality,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fusion.net/video/128220/watch-the-new-republics-jamil-smith-speaks-on-loretta-lynchs-task-in-baltimore/|title=WATCH: The New Republic's Jamil Smith Speaks on Loretta Lynch's Task in Baltimore|date=April 30, 2015|work=Fusion|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fusion.net/story/307458/louisiana-blue-lives-matter-bill-police/|title=Louisiana Just Passed a 'Blue Lives Matter' Bill That Makes Attacks Against Police Hate Crimes|last1=Tolan|first1=Casey|date=May 27, 2016|work=Fusion|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> feminism and gender roles,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mic.com/articles/144943/in-just-3-minutes-jamil-smith-nails-how-toxic-masculinity-fuels-rape-culture|title=In Just 3 Minutes, Jamil Smith Nails How Toxic Masculinity Fuels Rape Culture|last=Solis|first=Marie|date=June 1, 2016|work=Mic|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and national politics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/wp/2018/03/09/happy-hour-roundup-1313/|title=Opinion {{!}} Happy Hour Roundup|last1=Waldman|first1=Paul|date=March 9, 2018|work=Washington Post|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith joined ''[[The New Republic]]'' in January 2015, part of a wave of new hires following the 2014 removal of editor-in-chief [[Franklin Foer]], which prompted the departure of 55 staff members and contributors. Foer's replacement, Gabriel Snyder, hired Smith as a senior editor covering race, politics and gender.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/new-republic-makes-first-hires-following-staff-walkout-162217/|title=The New Republic Makes First Hires Following Staff Walkout|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> With the magazine facing criticism both from those upset by changes at the long-standing institution and also from those critical of the magazine's history, particularly its treatment of race-related topics, Smith described his role, with colleagues, as aiming \"to help usher this magazine into a different era.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/06/new-republic-jamil-smith-huffpost-live_n_6632458.html|title=New Republic Editor Jamil Smith Asks For Time Before Critics Declare Magazine Dead|last=Connor|first=Jackson|date=February 6, 2015|work=Huffington Post|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> While at ''The New Republic'', Smith also launched and hosted the magazine's first podcast, ''Intersection.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/video/jamil-smith-on-the-intersection-of-race-gender-and-politics-509680707887|title=Jamil Smith on the \"Intersection\" of Race, Gender and Politics|work=NBC News|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Smith became a senior national correspondent for [[MTV News]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/mtv-news-viacom-1201703599/|title=Viacom Reboots MTV News in First Step Toward Reviving Network|last1=Steinberg|first1=Brian|date=February 11, 2016|work=Variety|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> hired alongside writers and editors including [[Ana Marie Cox]], [[Jessica Hopper]], [[Charles Aaron]], [[Meredith Graves]], [[Doreen St. F\u00e9lix]] and [[Ira Madison III]] as part of a significant expansion of MTV News programming.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/02/mtv-wants-you-to-want-your-mtv-news-all-over-again/|title=MTV Wants You to Want Your MTV News All Over Again|last=Greenberg|first=Julia|date=February 11, 2016|work=Wired|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7849323/mtv-news-restructuring-shift-video|title=MTV Restructuring News Department, Shifting to Emphasis on Video (Updated)|last=Gensler|first=Andy|date=June 28, 2017|work=Billboard|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Among other on-air appearances for MTV, Smith served as a co-host, with [[Charlamagne tha God|Charlamagne Tha God]], [[Marc Lamont Hill]] and [[Franchesca Ramsey]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-what-now-mtv-bet-offer-town-hall-20160708-story.html|title='What Now?' MTV, BET offer town hall|last=Boedeker|first=Hal|date=July 8, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> of the joint MTV-[[BET]] townhall \"What Now\", following the police shooting deaths of [[Shooting of Alton Sterling|Alton Sterling]] and [[Shooting of Philando Castile|Philando Castile]] and the [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|shooting of police officers in Dallas]] that all took place in the first week of July 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-mtv-town-hall-addresses-909577|title='What Now?': MTV Town Hall Addresses Police Violence|last=Konerman|first=Jennifer|date=July 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref> At MTV, Smith also hosted ''The Racket,'' a [[YouTube]] series on politics, especially the [[2016 United States presidential election|US Presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/mtv-the-racket-digital-series-president-election-jamil-smith-1201755493/|title=MTV Bows Digital Series Covering \u2018Ridiculous\u2019 President Election Hosted by Jamil Smith|last1=Spangler|first1=Todd|date=April 18, 2016|work=Variety|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> He also appeared on the MTV News podcast ''The Stakes,'' including hosting an episode commemorating the 25th anniversary of the [[1992 Los Angeles riots|1992 Los Angeles uprising]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3023680/florence-and-normandie-25-years-after-the-l-a-riots/|title=Florence and Normandie: 25 Years After the L.A. Riots|work=MTV News|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter layoffs at MTV News in June 2017,<ref name=\":5\" /> Smith became a freelance reporter and opinion writer, writing (among other works) \"The Revolutionary Power of ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'',\" the cover story for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine\u2019s February 19, 2018 issue;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hellogiggles.com/news/black-panther-time-cover/|title=\"Black Panther\" made it on the cover of \"Time\" magazine, and here's why that's so important|last=Purdom|first=Gwendolyn|date=February 9, 2018|work=HelloGiggles|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> this made ''Black Panther'' the first [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film to be featured on ''Time''<nowiki/>'s cover.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thesource.com/2018/02/12/black-panther-star-chadwick-boseman-graces-time-magazine-cover-first-time-ever-marvel-movie/|title='Black Panther' Star Chadwick Boseman Graces Time Magazine Cover, First Time Ever For Marvel Movie|last=Allah|first=Sha Be|date=February 12, 2018|work=The Source|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In his analysis, Smith argued the film was culturally significant as proof that African-American narratives can be commercial successes with all audiences, as well as that \"making movies about black lives is part of showing that they matter.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/feb/15/black-panther-resistance|title=Black Panther is great. But let\u2019s not treat it as an act of resistance|last=Mtshali|first=Khanya Khondlo|date=February 15, 2018|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/black-panther/|title=The Revolutionary Power of Black Panther|last=Smith|first=Jamil|date=February 19, 2018|website=Time|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith joined ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as senior writer in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/03/rolling-stone-ryan-lizza-jann-gus-wenner-jay-penske-is-the-media-tycoon-du-jour|title=Can Rolling Stone Become Cool Again?|last=Pompeo|first=Joe|date=March 5, 2018|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nWhile a segment producer at NFL Films, Smith was part of teams that won the 2006 and 2009 Outstanding Studio Show \u2013 Weekly [[Sports Emmy Award|Sports Emmy]] for ''[[Inside the NFL]]''<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/2006/05|title=May {{!}} 2006 {{!}} The Emmy Awards|date=May 1, 2006|website=emmyonline.com|publisher=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> and the 2010 Outstanding Edited Sports Series/Anthology Sports Emmy for ''[[Hard Knocks (TV series)#Cincinnati Bengals (2009)|Hard Knocks: Training Camp With The Cincinnati Bengals]].''<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nSmith has repeatedly been named to [[The Root 100|''The Root'' 100]] list of leading black influencers, including in 2011 for his work on ''The Rachel Maddow Show'', in 2013 for his work on ''Melissa Harris-Perry'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thegrio.com/2013/11/21/msnbc-star-hosts-and-contributors-honored-at-the-root-100-2013-awards-gala-in-nyc/|title=MSNBC star hosts and contributors honored at The Root 100 2013 Awards Gala in NYC|last=Stodgill|first=Alexis Garrett|date=November 21, 2013|work=The Grio|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and in 2015 for his work at ''The New Republic'', where, ''The Root'' wrote, he \"hits on cultural touch points from [[campus rape]] to the [[Rev. Al Sharpton]], banging out a nice mix of opinion, headlines and original reporting.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 2017, Smith moved from [[Brooklyn, New York]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://clevelandmagazine.com/in-the-cle/sports/articles/that-man-made-me-a-cleveland-sports-fan|title=\u2018That Man Made Me a Cleveland Sports Fan\u2019|last=Goodrich|first=Barry|date=August 5, 2016|work=Cleveland Magazine|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> to [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chris Hayes]]\n* [[Gene Demby]]\n* [[Joy-Ann Reid]]\n* [[Larry Wilmore]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://twitter.com/JamilSmith Jamil Smith] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://instagram.com/jamilksmith Jamil Smith] on [[Instagram]]\n* {{imdb name|nm5584186}}\n* [https://newrepublic.com/authors/jamil-smith Jamil Smith archive] at ''[[The New Republic]]''\n* [http://www.mtv.com/news/author/jamsmith/ Jamil Smith archive] at [[MTV News]]\n* [https://www.rollingstone.com/contributor/jamil-smith Jamil Smith archive] at ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n* {{C-SPAN|Jamil Smith}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jamil}}\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The New Republic people]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:NFL Films people]]\n[[Category:Rolling Stone people]]\n[[Category:African-American journalists]]\n[[Category:African-American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Sports Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Viacom Media Networks people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:American magazine journalists]]\n[[Category:Opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:American political journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Shaker Heights, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the journalist|the actor|Jamil Walker Smith}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| pre-nominals   = \n| name               =  <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| post-nominals   = \n| image              =  JamilSmith.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| alt                = Headshot of Jamil Smith. He wears glasses, a green-and-black checked collared shirt and a blue Los Angeles Dodgers cap. He smiles, looking off-camera.\n| caption            = Smith in February 2018\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  {{birth date and age|1975|09|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| nationality        = American\n| citizenship        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Journalist|Television producer}}\n| years_active       = 2002&ndash;present\n| employer           = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| known_for          = \n|credits= {{hlist|''[[Inside The NFL]]''|''[[Hard Knocks (TV series)|Hard Knocks]]''|''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]''|[[Melissa Harris-Perry (TV series)|''Melissa Harris-Perry'']] }}\n| home_town          = \n| movement           = \n| boards             = \n| awards             = [[Sports Emmy Award]]s (2006, 2009 and 2010)\n| website            = {{URL|twitter.com/JamilSmith}}\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Jamil Smith''' (born September 23, 1975) is an American print and television journalist. His reporting and commentary deal with a range of political and cultural topics, including race, gender, national politics and pop culture. He has been a senior editor at ''[[The New Republic]]'', a senior national correspondent at [[MTV News]], and is now a senior writer for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.\n\nWhile a television segment producer for [[NFL Films]], Smith won three [[Sports Emmy Award]]s, in 2006, 2009 and 2010. He has also served as a producer for ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' and [[Melissa Harris-Perry (TV series)|''Melissa Harris-Perry'']].\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn September 23, 1975,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JamilSmith/status/911720756949782528|title=My first @nytopinion op-ed, published on my birthday.|last=Smith|first=Jamil|date=September 23, 2017|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.shaker.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=6GUIAI0&dasi=2YB|title=March 2018 Newsletter: Journalist Jamil Smith (\u201893) Returns to SHHS to Discuss His Career and his Time Magazine Cover Story on Black Panther|date=March 2018|website=Shaker Heights Schools|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> in [[Cleveland, Ohio]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/cleveland-native-and-senior-editor-at-the-new-republic-jamil-smith-talks-about-race-his-new-job-the-new-new-republic-and-how-the-media-shou/Content?oid=4568641|title=Cleveland Native and Senior Editor at The New Republic Jamil Smith Talks About His New Job, the New New Republic, and How the Media Should be Covering Race|last=Grzegorek|first=Vince|date=April 29, 2015|website=Cleveland Scene|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Smith attended [[Hawken School]] through eighth grade, then graduated from [[Shaker Heights High School]] in 1993.<ref name=\":1\" /> While at Shaker Heights High School, he wrote for the student newspaper, ''The Shakerite'', for four years,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://shakerite.com/campus-and-city/jamil-smith/23/2018/|title=From The Shakerite to Time Magazine|last=Sheperd|first=Lauren|date=February 23, 2018|work=The Shakerite|access-date=March 17, 2018|last2=Krouse|first2=Anna|language=en-US}}</ref> as well as participating in the wrestling and track teams<ref name=\":1\" /> and the school's Minority Achievement Community program, where black upperclassmen with high grade point averages mentor black freshman and sophomore boys with lower GPAs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSmith did his undergraduate work at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], graduating from the College of Arts and Sciences in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upenn.edu/gazette/0703/0703notes.html|title=Gazette: Alumni Notes|date=July\u2013August 2003|website=www.upenn.edu|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> While in college, Smith wrote for the campus student newspaper, ''[[The Daily Pennsylvanian]]'', and participated in Students Together Against Acquaintance Rape.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.acluohio.org/archives/blog-posts/ten-things-you-need-to-know-about-jamil-smith|title=Ten Things You Need to Know about Jamil Smith|last=Claytor|first=Ifeolu|date=October 5, 2017|website=www.acluohio.org|publisher=ACLU of Ohio|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He also studied abroad at [[King's College London|Kings College London]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\nAfter four years as an assistant at the [[William Morris Agency]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://storify.com/JamilSmith/on-writing-professionally|title=On writing professionally|last=Smith|first=Jamil|date=January 31, 2015|website=Storify|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref> Smith began his career in television and film production in 2002 as a production assistant with [[CNN]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He next went to [[HBO Sports]], then [[NFL Films]],<ref name=\":0\" /> where he worked on production teams that won three [[Sports Emmy Award|Sports Emmys]], two for ''[[Inside the NFL]]'' and another for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] installment of the [[Hard Knocks (TV series)|''Hard Knocks'']] series.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/sports_30th_winners|title=WINNERS OF 30th ANNUAL SPORTS EMMY\u00ae AWARDS ANNOUNCED BY NATIONAL ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS & SCIENCES, DICK EBERSOL HONORED WITH LIFETIME ACHIEVEMENT AWARD |date=April 27, 2009|website=emmyonline.com|publisher=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/sports_31st_winners|title=WINNERS OF 31st ANNUAL SPORTS EMMY\u00ae AWARDS ANNOUNCED BY NATIONAL ACADEMY OF TELEVISION ARTS & SCIENCES, JOHN MADDEN HONORED WITH LIFETIME ACHIEVEMENT AWARD |date=April 26, 2010|website=emmyonline.com|publisher=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, he joined [[MSNBC]], serving as a producer for both ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' and [[Melissa Harris-Perry (TV series)|''Melissa Harris-Perry'']].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/29/business/media/melissa-harris-perry-is-out-at-msnbc-cable-network-confirms.html|title=After Tense Weeks, Melissa Harris-Perry\u2019s MSNBC Show Is Canceled|last1=Koblin|first1=John|date=February 28, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.poynter.org/2015/the-new-republic-begins-replenishing-its-staff/311037/|title=The New Republic begins replenishing its staff|last1=Mullin|first1=Benjamin|date=January 7, 2015|work=Poynter|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs a journalist and commentator, Smith has drawn notice for work on a range of political and cultural topics, including race and racism,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/vice-dubuc-ceo.php|title=The media today: Facing a critical moment, Vice plans for change at the top|last1=Vernon|first1=Pete|date=March 13, 2018|work=Columbia Journalism Review|accessdate=March 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theroot.com/facewall/the-root-100-2015/#jamil_smith|title=The Root 100 \u2013 78 Jamil Smith|last=|first=|date=September 9, 2015|work=The Root|access-date=July 30, 2016|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919164038/http://www.theroot.com/facewall/the-root-100-2015/#jamil_smith|archive-date=September 19, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> police brutality,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fusion.net/video/128220/watch-the-new-republics-jamil-smith-speaks-on-loretta-lynchs-task-in-baltimore/|title=WATCH: The New Republic's Jamil Smith Speaks on Loretta Lynch's Task in Baltimore|date=April 30, 2015|work=Fusion|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fusion.net/story/307458/louisiana-blue-lives-matter-bill-police/|title=Louisiana Just Passed a 'Blue Lives Matter' Bill That Makes Attacks Against Police Hate Crimes|last1=Tolan|first1=Casey|date=May 27, 2016|work=Fusion|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> feminism and gender roles,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mic.com/articles/144943/in-just-3-minutes-jamil-smith-nails-how-toxic-masculinity-fuels-rape-culture|title=In Just 3 Minutes, Jamil Smith Nails How Toxic Masculinity Fuels Rape Culture|last=Solis|first=Marie|date=June 1, 2016|work=Mic|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and national politics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/wp/2018/03/09/happy-hour-roundup-1313/|title=Opinion {{!}} Happy Hour Roundup|last1=Waldman|first1=Paul|date=March 9, 2018|work=Washington Post|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith joined ''[[The New Republic]]'' in January 2015, part of a wave of new hires following the 2014 removal of editor-in-chief [[Franklin Foer]], which prompted the departure of 55 staff members and contributors. Foer's replacement, Gabriel Snyder, hired Smith as a senior editor covering race, politics and gender.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/new-republic-makes-first-hires-following-staff-walkout-162217/|title=The New Republic Makes First Hires Following Staff Walkout|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> With the magazine facing criticism both from those upset by changes at the long-standing institution and also from those critical of the magazine's history, particularly its treatment of race-related topics, Smith described his role, with colleagues, as aiming \"to help usher this magazine into a different era.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/06/new-republic-jamil-smith-huffpost-live_n_6632458.html|title=New Republic Editor Jamil Smith Asks For Time Before Critics Declare Magazine Dead|last=Connor|first=Jackson|date=February 6, 2015|work=Huffington Post|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> While at ''The New Republic'', Smith also launched and hosted the magazine's first podcast, ''Intersection.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/video/jamil-smith-on-the-intersection-of-race-gender-and-politics-509680707887|title=Jamil Smith on the \"Intersection\" of Race, Gender and Politics|work=NBC News|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Smith became a senior national correspondent for [[MTV News]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/mtv-news-viacom-1201703599/|title=Viacom Reboots MTV News in First Step Toward Reviving Network|last1=Steinberg|first1=Brian|date=February 11, 2016|work=Variety|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> hired alongside writers and editors including [[Ana Marie Cox]], [[Jessica Hopper]], [[Charles Aaron]], [[Meredith Graves]], [[Doreen St. F\u00e9lix]] and [[Ira Madison III]] as part of a significant expansion of MTV News programming.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/02/mtv-wants-you-to-want-your-mtv-news-all-over-again/|title=MTV Wants You to Want Your MTV News All Over Again|last=Greenberg|first=Julia|date=February 11, 2016|work=Wired|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7849323/mtv-news-restructuring-shift-video|title=MTV Restructuring News Department, Shifting to Emphasis on Video (Updated)|last=Gensler|first=Andy|date=June 28, 2017|work=Billboard|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Among other on-air appearances for MTV, Smith served as a co-host, with [[Charlamagne tha God|Charlamagne Tha God]], [[Marc Lamont Hill]] and [[Franchesca Ramsey]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-what-now-mtv-bet-offer-town-hall-20160708-story.html|title='What Now?' MTV, BET offer town hall|last=Boedeker|first=Hal|date=July 8, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> of the joint MTV-[[BET]] townhall \"What Now\", following the police shooting deaths of [[Shooting of Alton Sterling|Alton Sterling]] and [[Shooting of Philando Castile|Philando Castile]] and the [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|shooting of police officers in Dallas]] that all took place in the first week of July 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-mtv-town-hall-addresses-909577|title='What Now?': MTV Town Hall Addresses Police Violence|last=Konerman|first=Jennifer|date=July 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref> At MTV, Smith also hosted ''The Racket,'' a [[YouTube]] series on politics, especially the [[2016 United States presidential election|US Presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/mtv-the-racket-digital-series-president-election-jamil-smith-1201755493/|title=MTV Bows Digital Series Covering \u2018Ridiculous\u2019 President Election Hosted by Jamil Smith|last1=Spangler|first1=Todd|date=April 18, 2016|work=Variety|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> He also appeared on the MTV News podcast ''The Stakes,'' including hosting an episode commemorating the 25th anniversary of the [[1992 Los Angeles riots|1992 Los Angeles uprising]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3023680/florence-and-normandie-25-years-after-the-l-a-riots/|title=Florence and Normandie: 25 Years After the L.A. Riots|work=MTV News|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter layoffs at MTV News in June 2017,<ref name=\":5\" /> Smith became a freelance reporter and opinion writer, writing (among other works) \"The Revolutionary Power of ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'',\" the cover story for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine\u2019s February 19, 2018 issue;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hellogiggles.com/news/black-panther-time-cover/|title=\"Black Panther\" made it on the cover of \"Time\" magazine, and here's why that's so important|last=Purdom|first=Gwendolyn|date=February 9, 2018|work=HelloGiggles|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> this made ''Black Panther'' the first [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film to be featured on ''Time''<nowiki/>'s cover.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thesource.com/2018/02/12/black-panther-star-chadwick-boseman-graces-time-magazine-cover-first-time-ever-marvel-movie/|title='Black Panther' Star Chadwick Boseman Graces Time Magazine Cover, First Time Ever For Marvel Movie|last=Allah|first=Sha Be|date=February 12, 2018|work=The Source|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In his analysis, Smith argued the film was culturally significant as proof that African-American narratives can be commercial successes with all audiences, as well as that \"making movies about black lives is part of showing that they matter.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/feb/15/black-panther-resistance|title=Black Panther is great. But let\u2019s not treat it as an act of resistance|last=Mtshali|first=Khanya Khondlo|date=February 15, 2018|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/black-panther/|title=The Revolutionary Power of Black Panther|last=Smith|first=Jamil|date=February 19, 2018|website=Time|access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith joined ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as senior writer in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/03/rolling-stone-ryan-lizza-jann-gus-wenner-jay-penske-is-the-media-tycoon-du-jour|title=Can Rolling Stone Become Cool Again?|last=Pompeo|first=Joe|date=March 5, 2018|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nWhile a segment producer at NFL Films, Smith was part of teams that won the 2006 and 2009 Outstanding Studio Show \u2013 Weekly [[Sports Emmy Award|Sports Emmy]] for ''[[Inside the NFL]]''<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/2006/05|title=May {{!}} 2006 {{!}} The Emmy Awards|date=May 1, 2006|website=emmyonline.com|publisher=The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> and the 2010 Outstanding Edited Sports Series/Anthology Sports Emmy for ''[[Hard Knocks (TV series)#Cincinnati Bengals (2009)|Hard Knocks: Training Camp With The Cincinnati Bengals]].''<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nSmith has repeatedly been named to [[The Root 100|''The Root'' 100]] list of leading black influencers, including in 2011 for his work on ''The Rachel Maddow Show'', in 2013 for his work on ''Melissa Harris-Perry'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thegrio.com/2013/11/21/msnbc-star-hosts-and-contributors-honored-at-the-root-100-2013-awards-gala-in-nyc/|title=MSNBC star hosts and contributors honored at The Root 100 2013 Awards Gala in NYC|last=Stodgill|first=Alexis Garrett|date=November 21, 2013|work=The Grio|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and in 2015 for his work at ''The New Republic'', where, ''The Root'' wrote, he \"hits on cultural touch points from [[campus rape]] to the [[Rev. Al Sharpton]], banging out a nice mix of opinion, headlines and original reporting.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 2017, Smith moved from [[Brooklyn, New York]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://clevelandmagazine.com/in-the-cle/sports/articles/that-man-made-me-a-cleveland-sports-fan|title=\u2018That Man Made Me a Cleveland Sports Fan\u2019|last=Goodrich|first=Barry|date=August 5, 2016|work=Cleveland Magazine|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> to [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chris Hayes]]\n* [[Gene Demby]]\n* [[Joy-Ann Reid]]\n* [[Larry Wilmore]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://twitter.com/JamilSmith Jamil Smith] on [[Twitter]]\n* {{imdb name|nm5584186}}\n* [https://newrepublic.com/authors/jamil-smith Jamil Smith archive] at ''[[The New Republic]]''\n* [http://www.mtv.com/news/author/jamsmith/ Jamil Smith archive] at [[MTV News]]\n* [https://www.rollingstone.com/contributor/jamil-smith Jamil Smith archive] at ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n* {{C-SPAN|Jamil Smith}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jamil}}\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The New Republic people]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:NFL Films people]]\n[[Category:Rolling Stone people]]\n[[Category:African-American journalists]]\n[[Category:African-American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Sports Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Viacom Media Networks people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:American magazine journalists]]\n[[Category:Opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:American political journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Shaker Heights, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Jamilsmith", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamil_Smith_(journalist)"}
